Let's solve it now. Problem solved.

00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:07.460
Many Supreme Court cases are not unanimous.
In fact, in an ideologically divided court,

00:05:07.460 --> 00:05:11.590
you are likely to find a lot of cases decided
by 5 to 4 margins. The judges who are on the

00:05:11.590 --> 00:05:15.850
losing side who didn't support the majority
decision can write a dissenting opinion. A

00:05:15.850 --> 00:05:20.020
dissent does not set a precedent for a lower
court and has no force of law, but often dissents

00:05:20.020 --> 00:05:24.090
are very eloquent and they can provide arguments
that might persuade later courts in similar

00:05:24.090 --> 00:05:28.060
decisions. Sometimes, as with the famously
bad case of Plessy v. Ferguson, the arguments

00:05:28.060 --> 00:05:32.010
in a dissent can form the foundation for the
majority opinion in a later case, even though

00:05:32.010 --> 00:05:35.889
it can take 50 years to get from a case like
Plessy to Brown v. Board of Education.

00:05:35.889 --> 00:05:39.480
So that's the nuts and bolts of how Supreme
Court decisions are made. But before we wrap

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:42.980
this up, here are a few key things to remember.
First, there are a lot of hurdles you need

00:05:42.980 --> 00:05:47.540
to jump over before a court makes a decision
in a case. Most certiorari petitions, there

00:05:47.540 --> 00:05:51.550
are usually about 8,000 each year, don't make
it past the clerks or the solicitor general,

00:05:51.550 --> 00:05:56.139
and don't get granted. It takes 4 judges to
agree to hear a case, but 5 to render a majority

00:05:56.139 --> 00:06:00.050
opinion. Only the holding and the rationale
supported by at least 5 of the 9 justices

00:06:00.050 --> 00:06:04.320
becomes binding precedent for lower courts.
Dissents and concurrences may be fun and interesting

00:06:04.320 --> 00:06:08.020
to read, especially if there are pictures,
and they may include important legal ideas,

00:06:08.020 --> 00:06:11.310
but lower courts don't need to follow them.
So that's how to court works procedurally,

00:06:11.310 --> 00:06:15.060
but there's another way to think about Supreme
Court decision-making. To really understand

00:06:15.060 --> 00:06:19.290
the Supreme Court, we need to consider the
thinking behind judicial decisions, but that's

